social_posts.post_text: In honor of the Fall season coming to a close, we wanted to look back to when our quirky corner of Arkansas was dressed in brilliant reds and golds. 🍁 📷@TheJeffRose #BrandPartner

During fall color I had an sd card malfunction and I thought images from one of my favorite evening hikes this season with @lifeasmc had been lost. I recently was able to salvage some of the images, so here are a few scenes from along the Buffalo River Trail before the leaves fell 🍁
A few details from climbing up a random unnamed drainage after the rain this morning. I didn’t find any significant water features in this particular hollow but some nice little cascades 🌿
Maidenhair Fern & Falls out in the Ozarks 🌿
A few scenes from out at Sweden Creek Falls with @lifeasmc this evening
A year ago today I asked @lifeasmc to marry me under this beautiful waterfall.

Today is the official last day of Fall (even though the color has been gone for a while now). Here are ten of my favorite images taken during the colorful part of the season. All are now available as prints on my website www.jeffrose.photography

It’s the first official day of Winter and snow is likely to arrive tomorrow! Here’s one of my favorite winter images taken on a very cold morning along the Goat Trail on Big Bluff. Prints available at www.jeffrose.photography

This weather has me thinking about the extended cold spell in early 2021 (thankfully these temps won’t last as long as it did). Here is Glory Hole Falls frozen into a column of ice during that previous winter. Prints available at www.jeffrose.photography
Merry Christmas Eve y’all 🎄
Looking back on 2022 out in the Ozarks! It’s been an incredible year…from little adventures around Arkansas to the biggest adventure…marrying my best friend. Here’s a little glimpse inside my year.

With as many photographs as I take each year it’s always so hard to narrow down my favorites, but here are a few of the images I was thankful to of had the opportunity to capture while living in the beautiful Ozark Mountains this year (with a few from our honeymoon in Colorado as well)! All of these images are now available as prints on my website: www.jeffrose.photography

Exploring around Queen Wilhelmina State Park, Arkansas. Last week @lifeasmc and I took a little trip to Queen Wilhelmina and had such an incredible time exploring around the area! Here’s a little compilation of moments from our trip and I’ll be sharing more scenes throughout the week!

During our time at Queen Wilhelmina State Park @lifeasmc and I spent a lot of time taking in the sights along the Talimena Scenic Drive! There are so many incredible views along this stretch of road…here are a few scenes from our time there.

A few views along the Lovers Leap trail at Queen Wilhelmina State Park last week with @lifeasmc - This short trail has an incredible payoff with a sweeping view of Rich Mountain and the surrounding Ouachita National Forest!

Queen Wilhelmina State Park Itinerary.

1. Book your stay at Queen Wilhelmina Lodge…opt for a south facing second floor room for the best views!
2. Catch sunrise on the short hike to Lovers Leap Overlook. Difficulty: Moderate; Distance: 1.3 miles for the entire loop. 
3. Grab breakfast at the lodge.
4. Spend the afternoon driving the Talimena Scenic Byway and taking in the incredible sights.
5. Grab dinner in Mena at @theouachitasmena - great food and beverages.
6. Catch sunset at Grand View Vista along Talimena Scenic Byway on your way back to the lodge for the evening.

Sprite or red lightning over Arkansas. Last night was my first time to ever catch this elusive weather phenomenon on camera ⚡️

Sprites, are electrical discharges that appear as faint bursts of red light above clouds during thunderstorms. Because the weather phenomenon is so fleeting (sprites flash for just milliseconds) and for the most part not visible from the ground, they are difficult to observe and even more difficult to photograph, rather like the mischievous air spirits of the fantasy realm that they’re named for.
.
.
.

Fall in Arkansas 🍁

It won’t be long until autumn returns to the Natural State! I’m so excited for cooler temps, the elk rut, and ultimately the color change. As far as peak foliage: in the Arkansas Ozarks (where all this footage was taken) peak color typically arrives the last week of October through the second week of November, but this can vary year to year depending on temperature and rainfall.

Have you hiked the Goat Trail to Big Bluff?

It is one of my favorites and according to Alltrails it’s the second most popular trail in Arkansas! Don’t let the popularity fool you though…it is a 6-mile moderately strenuous hike with a good amount of elevation gain, and some rock scrambling. Not recommended for children or those afraid of heights!
.

One of the largest natural bridges in Arkansas! This Sandstone arch is 130 feet long and 20 feet wide. The trail is rated moderate due to some rock scrambling (rocks under the natural bridge can be very slippery at times), but the loop trail is just over a mile in length with less than 300 feet of elevation gain and takes you by many other beautiful sights along the way…including more arches, caves and wet-weather falls and streams. 

This is a few scenes from last night down in Alum Cove. It was great to get out and take advantage of the cool evening with @lifeasmc - it’s definitely beginning to feel a lot more like fall out in the Ozarks! 
.

Tag who you’re inviting to the Grey Horse Cabin ✨

@lifeasmc and I had the perfect anniversary getaway to the Grey Horse cabin at @inthetreesresort in Hot Springs, Arkansas. Tucked away in the Ouachitas surrounded by nature but close enough to downtown Hot Springs for us to easily experience the shops, restaurants, and National Park ❤️ There are hiking and biking trails around the property but we spent most of our time enjoying the amenities…soaking in the hot tub, lounging by the fire, and listening to vinyl on the record player.
